The chain at the bottom of the widget is the key thing to hold in your head. There are seven variables, but really just one story:\cb1 \
\cb7 You make one decision \'97\'a0
\f18\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf9 \cb10 \strokec9 x_\{i,z,t,p\}
\f11\fs24 \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 \'a0\'97 and everything else cascades from it. The\'a0
\f18\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf9 \cb10 \strokec9 x_\{i,t\}
\f11\fs24 \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 \'a0collapsed view lets the solver check type conflicts without re-examining all zone and persona combinations. The two\'a0
\f18\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf9 \cb10 \strokec9 u
\f11\fs24 \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 \'a0flags are timers running in the background, watching how long each type and each persona has been visible; when either expires, they flip to 1 and silently kill all credit from that deployment. The\'a0
\f18\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf9 \cb10 \strokec9 c
\f11\fs24 \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 \'a0detection event only fires when something real and undiscovered is present \'97 both flags must be zero. From there,\'a0
\f18\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf9 \cb10 \strokec9 p
\f11\fs24 \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 \'a0asks whether this hop on this path is now covered, and\'a0
\f18\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf9 \cb10 \strokec9 e
\f11\fs24 \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 \'a0asks whether that coverage happened early enough to count as prevention rather than forensics.\cb1 \
\cb7 The two discovery flags are the subtlest part. They are independent of each other on purpose. Rotating the type resets\'a0
\f18\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf9 \cb10 \strokec9 u_\{i,z,t\}
\f11\fs24 \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 \'a0but leaves\'a0
\f18\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf9 \cb10 \strokec9 u_\{i,z,t,p\}
\f11\fs24 \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 \'a0running. Rotating the persona resets\'a0
\f18\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf9 \cb10 \strokec9 u_\{i,z,t,p\}
\f11\fs24 \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 \'a0but leaves\'a0
\f18\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf9 \cb10 \strokec9 u_\{i,z,t\}
\f11\fs24 \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 \'a0running. An attacker who fingerprints by type and an attacker who fingerprints by identity signature are two different adversaries, and the model needs two separate clocks to stay ahead of both simultaneously.\cb1 \

