\f15\b0 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Try flipping either discovery toggle \'97 notice the credit collapses to exactly zero regardless of every other slider. That's the kill switch property in action.\
Here's the plain-language story of how the three equations connect:\

\f16\b Equation 2 (\uc0\u7813 ) answers: how much does location matter?
\f15\b0  The d
\f5 \uc0\u8344 
\f15 /h
\f13 \uc0\u7496 
\f15  ratio is a number between 0 and 1 that captures the rotation regime at each asset. A honeypot at the perimeter has to move frequently (small h
\f13 \uc0\u7496 
\f15 ) but can arrive fast (small d
\f5 \uc0\u8344 
\f15 ) \'97 the ratio stays moderate. A deep interior asset needs long dwell time to attract an attacker (large d
\f5 \uc0\u8344 
\f15 ) but also has a tighter rotation deadline (small h
\f13 \uc0\u7496 
\f15 ) \'97 the ratio can be high, boosting the weight. Assets where you can neither dwell long enough nor rotate fast enough get penalised.\

\f16\b Equation 3 (W) answers: how much does sensitivity matter?
\f15\b0  The (1 + \uc0\u963 ) multiplier is elegantly simple \'97 it says a completely blind honeypot (\u963  = 0) contributes nothing beyond its topology value, while a maximally sensitive one (\u963  = 1) doubles it. There's no discontinuity and no magic threshold. More sensitivity always helps, just at diminishing returns because you're bounded at 2\'d7.\

\f16\b Equation 4 (PW) answers: does any of this matter for this specific path?
\f15\b0  Multiplying by \uc0\u961 \u960  \'d7 iv\u960 ,h scales everything down to what actually matters operationally. The world's most sensitive honeypot at a perfectly positioned asset still earns zero credit on a path the attacker never uses (\u961 \u960  \u8776  0) or toward a target with no value (iv \u8776  0).\

\f16\b The persona extension then asks two final questions.
\f15\b0  First, will this persona attract this attacker? (q
\f5 \uc0\u8346 
\f15  \'97 scales credit up or down based on LLM threat classification.) Second, has anything been discovered? The two 
\f17\fs26 (1 \uc0\u8722  u)
\f15\fs24  terms are not soft penalties \'97 they are hard switches. The moment either fires, the product is zero. This is why discovery is so catastrophic to the solver's plan: it doesn't reduce credit, it eliminates it entirely from that deployment for all remaining slots until rotation resets the flag.\
