\f15\b0 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 The four categories, in plain terms:\

\f16\b Reality checks (C1, C6, C7) \'97 teal.
\f15\b0  These three constraints enforce honesty in the credit system. C1 says you cannot claim a detection without a real, undiscovered honeypot present. C6 says you cannot claim a path hop is covered without an actual detection firing there. C7 says you cannot claim prevention credit if the detection only happened at the final hop \'97 that's forensics, not prevention. Together they form a chain: deployment 
\f13 \uc0\u8594 
\f15  detection 
\f13 \uc0\u8594 
\f15  coverage 
\f13 \uc0\u8594 
\f15  prevention, with each link requiring proof of the link below it.\

\f16\b Physical limits (C2, C3, C4, C5, C5b) \'97 blue.
\f15\b0  These five constraints reflect things the network simply cannot do. C2 and C3 are budget walls \'97 one global, one per zone, and zones cannot borrow from each other. C4 is about service interference \'97 some types share infrastructure and cannot run simultaneously. C5 is a cable that doesn't exist \'97 an air-gapped zone cannot host a honeypot that needs cross-zone connectivity. C5b (new) adds believability \'97 a persona must actually be plausible for the hardware and zone it runs on.\

\f16\b Time and gap control (C8, C9, C10, C11) \'97 amber.
\f15\b0  These four constraints exist because of the patient attacker. Without them, a sophisticated adversary just maps your schedule and waits for the quiet month. C8 caps operational churn so the schedule stays humanly manageable. C9 burns a honeypot type when it has been visible long enough for the attacker to fingerprint the underlying service. C10 closes gap windows on high-probability paths \'97 the minimum covered slots is mathematically enforced. C11 (new) makes the rotation deadline dynamic \'97 rising threat intelligence automatically tightens the window, no human intervention needed.\

\f16\b Identity integrity (C12, C13) \'97 pink, new.
\f15\b0  These two constraints exist because type-rotation alone is not enough. An attacker who fingerprints at the identity level \'97 hostname, certificate, behavioral signature \'97 can track a honeypot even as it cycles through types. C12 prevents two honeypots from wearing the same identity simultaneously in the same zone, because duplicate identities immediately expose the deception. C13 burns a persona identity after it has been visible for too long, independently of the type burn timer, and restores full credit when a different persona is adopted.\
The enforcement spine at the bottom of the diagram is the key structural point: credit only flows when a deployment passes all four category checks simultaneously. A failure in any one category \'97 phantom credit, physical impossibility, open time window, or burned identity \'97 collapses the credit to zero regardless of how well the other three are satisfied.\
