\f16 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Layer 1 \'97 topology adjustment (\uc0\u7813 ).
\f15\b0  Start with the base importance of watching for a technique at a particular asset, then multiply by the ratio d
\f5 \uc0\u8344 
\f15 /h
\f13 \uc0\u7496 
\f15 . That ratio is always between 0 and 1. It captures the rotation regime: a high ratio means the honeypot gets to dwell for a long time relative to how often it must rotate \'97 deep interior assets. A low ratio means it barely settles in before it has to move \'97 perimeter assets. The formula rewards the former and penalises the latter because a honeypot that can't dwell long enough to attract an attacker is worth less regardless of how important the technique is.\

\f16\b Layer 2 \'97 stealth adjustment (W).
\f15\b0  Take the topology weight and multiply by (1 + \uc0\u963 ). Because \u963  is between 0 and 1, this factor is always between 1.0 and 2.0. A completely blind honeypot adds nothing \'97 weight unchanged at 1.0\'d7. A maximally sensitive one nearly doubles it at 2.0\'d7. The formula is deliberately bounded: sensitivity helps, but can never make a bad-location honeypot good.\

\f16\b Layer 3 \'97 full credit (the product of all six factors).
\f15\b0  The base formulation multiplies W by path probability \uc0\u961 \u960  and interception value iv\u960 ,h \'97 scaling everything to what actually matters for this specific path at this specific hop. The persona extension then adds two more factors: qp (how attractive this persona is to the current threat actor, set by the LLM from STIX intelligence) and the dual discovery guards (1\u8722 u_type)(1\u8722 u_persona). The guards are the critical structure: they are binary switches, not soft penalties. The moment either flag fires, the entire product collapses to zero \'97 it doesn't matter how good the topology is, how sensitive the honeypot is, or how well the persona matches the threat profile. Discovery on either axis wipes everything.\
