\f15\b0 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Fire all three signals in sequence to see how the persona priors shift for different threat profiles. Here's the plain-language explanation of what each step actually does and why Step 3 matters most:\

\f16\b Steps 1 and 2 \'97 pure solver mechanics, inherited unchanged.
\f15\b0  When STIX pushes updated path probabilities \uc0\u961 
\f13 \uc0\u8242 
\f15 \uc0\u960 , the algorithm recomputes the path weight PW
\f13 \uc0\u8242 
\f15  = \uc0\u961 
\f13 \uc0\u8242 
\f15 \'b7iv\'b7W for every path and updates the L3/L4 soft-clause weights accordingly. The hard constraints C1\'96C13 are never touched \'97 the feasibility boundary of the problem stays fixed. This is what makes warm-starting valid: the solution structure from x* is still legal under the new weights.\

\f16\b Step 3 \'97 the LLM contribution, and why it is a different kind of task.
\f15\b0  The LLM is not nudging anonymous weight values. It is reading a STIX signal \'97 "financially motivated actor with 88% confidence, TTPs matching FIN7/Carbanak" \'97 and producing a named judgment: raise Finance_DB and HR_workstation, lower OT_controller and DevOps_server. This judgment requires contextual reasoning that a SAT solver cannot perform from constraint structure alone. A solver knows that Finance_DB is in zone Z with cost C and covers technique T1078. It does not know that financially motivated attackers historically prioritise payroll data, that HR systems are a common lateral movement pivot in financial sector intrusions, or that OT infrastructure is irrelevant to this threat actor's known TTPs. The LLM holds that knowledge and translates it into the q
\f5 \uc0\u8346 
\f15  vector.\

\f16\b Why q
\f5\b0 \uc0\u8346 
\f16\b  is more interpretable than anonymous weight adjustment.
\f15\b0  If the LLM adjusted w
\f19 \uc0\u11388 
\f15  values directly, the output would be a vector of numbers \'97 w
\f20 \uc0\u8323 
\f15  changed from 1000 to 1102, w
\f20 \uc0\u8322 
\f15  changed from 100 to 87 \'97 that an operator cannot evaluate without reverse-engineering the entire objective function. The q
\f5 \uc0\u8346 
\f15  output is instead a named priority schedule: "this month, Finance_DB at 0.42, HR_workstation at 0.31, OT_controller at 0.04." A security operator can read that sentence, check it against their own threat intelligence, and override a specific persona if domain knowledge warrants \'97 all without touching any solver parameter. That is the difference between an opaque weight vector and an operationally interpretable output.\

\f16\b Steps 4\'967 \'97 fast re-certification, not a full re-solve.
\f15\b0  The warm-start from x* means RC2 inherits the previous solution as its starting point and only needs to verify that it remains optimal under the updated soft-clause weights and q
\f5 \uc0\u8346 
\f15  values. At XLarge scale this takes under 5 seconds. The \uc0\u916  check in Step 6 provides an audit log of every adaptation: every time the plan changes, the Q-score improvement is recorded. If the updated threat model produces no improvement over the current plan \'97 \u916  \u8804  0 \'97 the algorithm explicitly logs "still optimal" and makes no change, rather than deploying a different plan just because the inputs changed.\
