\f16 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 The cross-path multiplier comes from topology, not from the solver.
\f15\b0  Zone 2 happens to sit on all three attack paths at hop 2. That is a property of the network graph, not something the solver arranges. What the solver does is discover this fact \'97 by resolving the L3 clauses for all three paths simultaneously in a single UNSAT-core step \'97 and collect credit from all three in one deployment decision. Greedy cannot do this because it evaluates paths serially: it picks the web
\f13 \uc0\u8594 
\f15 db path first (highest \uc0\u961  = 0.30), commits budget to that decision, and then evaluates OT infiltration and brute
\f13 \uc0\u8594 
\f15 AD with whatever is left. It never asks "which single deployment satisfies the most clauses at once?" \'97 it only asks "what is the best deployment for the path I am looking at right now?"\

\f16\b The 2.1\'d7 RC2-vs-greedy ratio is preserved at default q
\f5\b0 \uc0\u8346 
\f16\b .
\f15\b0  When q
\f5 \uc0\u8346 
\f15  is the uniform prior 1/|P| \'97 meaning the LLM has no opinion about which persona is relevant \'97 the persona factor cancels out identically across RC2 and greedy and the ratio stays at the base-paper value of \uc0\u8776 2.1\'d7. This is the backward compatibility guarantee: the persona extension does not degrade the force-multiplier advantage when the LLM has nothing to say.\

\f16\b The persona lift is independent of the cross-path advantage, and they compound.
\f15\b0  When STIX signals a financially motivated actor and the LLM raises q_\{HR_workstation\} from 0.20 to 0.40, every path covered by the HR_workstation persona at Zone 2 earns 0.40/0.20 = 2.0\'d7 more credit. This lift is a property of the threat intelligence \'97 it says nothing about the topology. The cross-path advantage is a property of the topology \'97 it says nothing about the threat intelligence. Both are factors in the same product: credit = \uc0\u961 \'b7iv\'b7W\'b7q
\f5 \uc0\u8346 
\f15 . They multiply each other, so the combined advantage over greedy at default prior is the cross-path ratio \'d7 the persona lift ratio \'97 in the example above, approximately 2.1 \'d7 2.0 = 4.2\'d7 per deployment decision.\

\f16\b The base-paper RC2 total without q
\f5\b0 \uc0\u8346 
\f16\b  is 3.612, not 1.445.
\f15\b0  The table shows 1.445 because q
\f5 \uc0\u8346 
\f15  = 0.40 scales the whole product down from the no-persona case. If q
\f5 \uc0\u8346 
\f15  were 1.0 \'97 no persona layer \'97 the same three paths at the same W = 3.24 give the base-paper total of 3.612. The persona extension does not increase absolute credit at default prior; it adds a new axis of variation that the LLM can push above or below default depending on threat intelligence.\
