\f16 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 The schedule is a solution to eight simultaneous pressures, not eight independent decisions.
\f15\b0  Every row's pattern is explained by one or two constraints pulling against each other. The solver finds the arrangement that satisfies all hard constraints while maximising the soft-clause credit \'97 and the STIX update at t=2 changes two of those pulls mid-horizon, causing exactly two cells to flip.\

\f16\b What the STIX update actually does to the schedule.
\f15\b0  Before the update, db_trap/Cloud/Finance_DB was planned ON, ON, OFF, ON across the four slots. After the update, C10 tightens (the web
\f13 \uc0\u8594 
\f15 db path now needs at least three covered slots given the raised threat probability), forcing t=3 from OFF to ON. But now Finance_DB has run at t=1, t=2, and t=3 consecutively \'97 hitting the \uc0\u964 
\f13 \uc0\u7496 \u7510 
\f15  limit. C13 fires and forces a persona swap at t=4. The solver picks HR_workstation as the substitute (the only available persona in Cloud at t=4 that doesn't conflict with C12), creating the previously all-OFF row 6 as a new active deployment.\

\f16\b Why some rows are completely unaffected.
\f15\b0  scada_trap/OT/Generic_Linux runs all four slots because the air-gap constraint C5 means no rotation is possible and no threat signal changes the situation \'97 the financially motivated attacker has shown no interest in OT systems. ad_trap/Mgmt/HR_workstation is unaffected because the STIX update raises its persona credit (higher qp) but does not trigger any constraint that would change its schedule. Higher credit for an already-always-on deployment changes the objective value but not the binary deployment decisions.\

\f16\b The C12 row (db_trap/Cloud/HR_workstation, t=1\'96t=2 blocked) explains itself by what is absent.
\f15\b0  Finance_DB already occupies Cloud at t=1 and t=2. C12 says two honeypots cannot wear the same persona in the same zone at the same slot \'97 but these are different personas. The constraint that matters here is that the solver has no reason to put a second db_trap in Cloud at t=1 and t=2 when Finance_DB is already there earning credit. The row is OFF at those slots not because it violates C12 but because adding it would consume budget for zero additional credit. C12 only becomes relevant after the STIX update forces Finance_DB to vacate at t=4 and HR_workstation must fill the gap.
