\f14\fs37\fsmilli18667 \cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
I. Complexity
\f0\b0\fs53\fsmilli26667 \cf8 \

\f1\b\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \
\
{{\NeXTGraphic Pasted Graphic 23.png \width25280 \height16560 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}洞\
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f16 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Two numbers, two different things.
\f15\b0  Primary variables answer "what decisions does the solver make?" Clause database answers "how much work does it take to evaluate those decisions?" These are independent. A small decision space does not mean a fast solve. A large decision space does not mean a slow solve. The difficulty lives in the clause database.\

\f16\b Why variables stay flat.
\f15\b0  The solver decides which zone category to deploy in, not which specific host to place a honeypot on. Zone has five values \'97 DMZ, Internal, OT, Cloud, Management \'97 and this does not change as the enterprise grows. A 50-host site and a 50,000-host enterprise have the same five zone categories. The primary variable count is always |K|\'b7|Z|\'b7H\'b7|P| = 8\'d75\'d74\'d74 = 640 at XLarge with four personas and four slots. This is a deliberate design choice: intra-zone heterogeneity is captured through aggregated weights W_\{j,a\} and per-zone budgets B_z, not through per-host variables.\

\f16\b Why the clause database grows.
\f15\b0  For every combination of honeypot type, asset, ATT&CK technique, time slot, and persona, there is a clause asking: does this honeypot, in this zone, this month, wearing this identity, detect this technique against this asset? At XLarge with 500,000 assets, 8 types, 18 techniques, 4 slots, and 4 personas, that is approximately 500,000 \'d7 8 \'d7 18 \'d7 4 \'d7 4 = 1.15 billion potential clause interactions. RC2 processes these through core-guided search \'97 which is why it takes 30 seconds rather than milliseconds. Per-zone decomposition cuts this by partitioning assets into five independent sub-problems solved in parallel, keeping per-core runtime tractable.\

\f16\b The hospital analogy precisely.
\f15\b0  Deciding which eight departments to station nurses in is a 40-variable problem (8 departments \'d7 5 shifts). That never changes regardless of hospital size. But calculating the actual patient-coverage impact of each assignment across 50,000 daily patient interactions is where the computation lives \'97 and that scales with patient count. The variable count and the problem difficulty are completely different things.\

\f16\b NP-hardness lives in the clause database, not the variable count.
\f15\b0  The reduction from Weighted Maximum Coverage (Feige 1998) is constructed over the |A|\'b7|T| asset-technique coverage structure \'97 the clause database. This is why the hardness result holds even though the primary variable count is small in practice: you could enumerate all 640 primary variable combinations in milliseconds, but evaluating which combination best covers 1.15 billion clause interactions is what makes the problem hard. Adding personas (|P|>1) introduces the C12 persona-conflict clause class, which has no analogue in the base reduction, making the extended problem strictly harder \'97 the NP-hardness is not just preserved but strengthened.
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 \
