\cf0 The weight formula combines these: a honeypot protecting oracle-prod at hop 1 earns 3.5 / 1 = 3.5 units of weight. The same honeypot at hop 3 earns only 3.5 / 3 = 1.17 units. This is the mathematical encoding of a simple security truth \'97 stopping an attacker before they reach the target is worth far more than catching them after they arrive.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f16\b \cf0 Why it matters:
\f15\b0  Without A, the solver cannot calculate what catching an attacker is actually worth. It would treat all detection events as equally valuable. A makes the solver prefer zones with high-value, close-to-entry assets \'97 which is exactly where experienced security teams put their best sensors.\
\
Z = \{\
  DMZ,       \'97 internet-facing, highest attack exposure\
  Internal,  \'97 office network, lateral movement hub\
  Cloud,     \'97 AWS-hosted, mixed trust\
  OT,        \'97 industrial systems, physically isolated\
  Management \'97 network infrastructure, highest privilege\
\}\
\

\f16\b Why the zones are structural, not just labels:
\f15\b0 \
Zone boundaries enforce three real constraints on what the solver can do:\
First, 
\f16\b air gaps.
\f15\b0  The OT zone is physically isolated from the DMZ and Cloud zones. There is no network cable connecting them. The solver cannot place a web_trap in the OT zone because the web_trap needs to receive HTTP connections from the internet, and the internet cannot reach OT. No matter how valuable such a deployment would theoretically be, the physical wire does not exist.\
Second, 
\f16\b eligibility.
\f15\b0  The scada_trap speaks industrial protocols \'97 Modbus, DNP3, OPC-UA. These protocols only exist in the OT zone. Deploying a scada_trap in the Cloud zone would be like putting a deep-sea diving suit in a shopping mall \'97 nobody there has any reason to interact with it.\
Third, 
\f16\b per-zone budgets.
\f15\b0  The OT team and the network security team have separate budget lines. B_\{OT\} = 2,000 units per month. Even if the global budget B has unused room, the solver cannot spend more than 2,000 in OT. A second scada_trap (cost 2.0) is blocked not because the global budget is exhausted but because the zone sub-limit is fully consumed.\

\f16\b How zones shape the solver's decisions:
\f15\b0 \
The five zones create a structured search space. The solver does not evaluate every possible host \'97 it evaluates every possible (honeypot type, zone) pair. An 8-type \'d7 5-zone space gives 40 combinations per time slot. Most of these are immediately eliminated by eligibility rules (scada_trap only in OT), air-gap constraints (no web_trap in OT), and budget limits (no second scada_trap when B_\{OT\} is spent). What remains is a small, well-constrained problem that RC2 can solve to certified optimality in seconds.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\f16\b \cf0 How K, T, A, Z fit together\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f15\b0 \cf0 These four sets define the skeleton of the problem before a single deployment decision is made:\
