\f16\b \cf0 Why interception values decrease as hops increase:
\f15\b0 \
This is not arbitrary. It reflects a genuine security principle: the further along the path the attacker has traveled, the less catching them prevents. At hop 1 you prevent the entire intrusion. At hop 2 you prevent the final target compromise but not the initial access. At hop 3 you record the breach but do not prevent it.\
The L4 soft clause in the objective reinforces this with a 1000\'d7 weight on early interception. The first non-final-hop coverage of any path earns the prevention bonus \'97 the single highest-weighted event in the entire formulation. This forces the solver to always maintain at least one prevention-layer honeypot on every path regardless of what other credit is available.\

