\f16\b \cf0 C 
\f4\b0 \uc0\u8838 
\f16\b  K\'d7K \'97 Pairwise Conflict Set (honeypots that cannot coexist)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f15\b0 \cf0 C is the set of honeypot type pairs that cannot run simultaneously in the same time slot. Each pair (k
\f13 \uc0\u7522 
\f15 , k
\f5 \uc0\u8343 
\f15 ) in C means: if you deploy type k
\f13 \uc0\u7522 
\f15 , you cannot also deploy type k
\f5 \uc0\u8343 
\f15  that month, and vice versa.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f16\b \cf0 Why conflicts exist \'97 three real reasons:
\f15\b0 \

\f16\b Reason 1 \'97 Shared monitoring pipeline.
\f15\b0  Two honeypots that capture the same attacker behavior flood the same logging system with duplicate alerts. The monitoring team cannot tell the signals apart. What looks like doubled coverage is actually doubled noise with no additional detection value.\

\f16\b Reason 2 \'97 Shared physical infrastructure.
\f15\b0  Some honeypot types require the same network tap, the same monitoring server, or the same logging database. Running both simultaneously overloads the shared resource and degrades the quality of both.\

\f16\b Reason 3 \'97 Contradictory network signals.
\f15\b0  Two honeypots presenting conflicting identities on the same network segment can confuse each other's deception. An attacker scanning the network sees inconsistent behavior and correctly infers that something artificial is present.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\
C = \{\
  (generic_trap, dns_trap),    \'97 both capture T1046 network scanning;\
                                 running both saturates the same SIEM\
                                 alert queue without additional coverage\
\
  (web_trap, generic_trap),    \'97 both expose HTTP services; generic_trap\
                                 mimics web behavior and creates ambiguous\
                                 signals when web_trap is also present\
\
  (smb_trap, generic_trap),    \'97 both capture T1021 SMB lateral movement;\
                                 duplicate signals confuse incident response\
\}\
\
