\f16\b \cf0 Why dividing by h
\f6 \uc0\u7496 
\f16  is the right choice:
\f15\b0 \
Imagine the web-to-database attack path \uc0\u960 
\f20 \uc0\u8321 
\f15 :\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\
Hop 1 \'97 DMZ web server:\
  Attacker has entered through the web portal.\
  No internal data accessed yet.\
  Catching here = full prevention.\
  Damage prevented: 100% of the potential breach.\
\
Hop 2 \'97 Internal LAN:\
  Attacker has crossed the DMZ and is moving through\
  the internal network. They have conducted reconnaissance.\
  Catching here = prevent database breach but not\
  the initial perimeter compromise.\
  Damage prevented: roughly 70% of the potential breach.\
\
Hop 3 \'97 Oracle database:\
  Attacker has reached the database. They may have\
  already run queries. Catching here = forensic evidence\
  but the database was accessible.\
  Damage prevented: roughly 30% \'97 attribution only.\
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Dividing by h
\f13 \uc0\u7496 
\f15  makes the value at hop 1 three times the value at hop 3, which roughly matches the actual damage-prevention ratio. The formula is not perfectly calibrated \'97 no formula could be \'97 but it is in the right direction and the right order of magnitude.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

